snippet.textDisplay: In 2009, Quentin Tarantino named Supercop as one of his 20 favorite films since 1992 (his directorial debut) due to it having "the greatest stunts ever filmed in any movie ever". Further cementing his praise in 2016 by declaring that the final sequence is the one that he would like to preserve forever for future generations and aliens to witness. The pairing of Michelle Yeoh and Jackie Chan in their primes really was a recipe for absolute stunt work insanity.

snippet.textDisplay: I think you guys could get a lot out of analyzing the 2002 Yimou Zhang film "Hero," both stunt and special fx wise. Also, when you guys were talking about the wire work in "Crouching Tiger, Hidden Dragon" I think the wire work in "Hero" is something that's also done really well; the slack in the wire is just right so that it looks like the actors are actually running on air as opposed to flailing their legs around.
snippet.textOriginal: I think you guys could get a lot out of analyzing the 2002 Yimou Zhang film "Hero," both stunt and special fx wise. Also, when you guys were talking about the wire work in "Crouching Tiger, Hidden Dragon" I think the wire work in "Hero" is something that's also done really well; the slack in the wire is just right so that it looks like the actors are actually running on air as opposed to flailing their legs around.
